# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
overview:<p>The Grand Dragon emerged from Luthien Armor Works' efforts to modernize the venerable Dragon chassis using newly recovered Star League technology. What began as a simple field modification replacing the autocannon with a particle projection cannon evolved into a full production model by 3040. Over the following fifteen years, LAW systematically converted Dragon production lines at Luthien, Dieron, Saffel, and Yorii to Grand Dragon manufacture, completely phasing out the original by 3055.</p><p>The Grand Dragon represented the Combine's technological renaissance following the recovery of the Helm Memory Core. The design maintained the Dragon's characteristic speed and versatility while incorporating significant improvements. Production continued until the Word of Blake's devastating 3068 attacks on LAW facilities, though rapid establishment of new factories ensured the Grand Dragon's continued service.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Grand Dragon's combat effectiveness stems from its successful integration of advanced technology without sacrificing the original Dragon's core strengths. The Hermes 360 XL engine pushes the sixty-ton chassis to a maximum speed of 97 kilometers per hour, making it one of the faster heavy 'Mechs in DCMS service. This mobility combines with the Lord's Light 2 Extended-Range PPC to create a highly effective skirmisher capable of dictating engagement ranges. The Telos DecaCluster LRM-10 provides supplementary firepower, while three Victory 23R medium lasers handle close defense.</p><p>Thirteen double heat sinks manage the thermal load efficiently, allowing sustained fire with the primary weapons. CASE-protected ammunition storage demonstrates LAW's attention to survivability. The enhanced hip and torso assembly developed at Nykvarn increased torso rotation from 250 degrees to nearly 300 degrees, substantially improving the 'Mech's ability to engage targets across wider firing arcs. This modification became standard on all Grand Dragons produced after the Jihad. However, the XL engine that enables the Grand Dragon's impressive speed also serves as a significant vulnerability, as penetrating damage to either torso section can disable the 'Mech entirely.</p>

deployment:<p>A Jihad-era customization of the 7K platform, this configuration incorporates post-Clan Invasion technology for improved performance. Ferro-fibrous armor and a light engine save weight while maintaining protection, allowing retention of the LRM-15 rather than the problematic MRM system. A Heavy PPC replaces the prototype ER Large Laser, substantially increasing ranged firepower at the cost of heat management complexity. A C3 slave unit and MASC round out the upgrade package, creating a variant that addresses several criticisms of the standard 7K while introducing its own tactical considerations.</p>

history:<p>The Grand Dragon's development traces back to the waning years of the Fourth Succession War, when DCMS commanders began experimenting with field modifications to their Dragon 'Mechs. The most successful of these swapped the autocannon for a particle projection cannon, creating what would become the DRG-1G configuration. Initial reception proved enthusiastic enough that LAW formalized the design for production in 3040.</p><p>Acceptance within the DCMS came rapidly as the Grand Dragon reached line units throughout the 3040s and 3050s. The 'Mech's effective combination of speed, firepower, and heat management made it popular with MechWarriors who appreciated its versatility. Nearly every DCMS line unit eventually fielded a company of Dragons or Grand Dragons. The Grand Dragon also saw extensive use during the Clan Invasion, where its mobility proved valuable against technologically superior Clan opponents.</p><p>The Jihad brought severe disruption when Word of Blake forces struck LAW's primary facilities between 3068 and 3070. LAW's resilience proved equal to the challenge, as the company established new manufacturing capacity within two years. The Nykvarn facility earned the honor of restarting Grand Dragon production, followed by rebuilt facilities on Abiy Adi and Savinsville. Post-Jihad variants continued the chassis's evolution, incorporating C3 networks, improved missiles, and eventually Clan-grade technology.</p>

